	        Send us your pictures   ·  Send us your stories Madrid - The European Union's law enforcement agency says police have smashed a Nigerian organised crime ring in one of the largest European operations against human trafficking. Europol says the Nigerian gang trafficked victims to Europe through Libya and Italy, forcing women into prostitution to pay for their journey. Spain's Guardia Civil carried out 41 house searches in 11 Spanish cities, while Britain's National Crime Agency mounted raids in Manchester. Europol says the criminal ring was active in multiple EU countries. A Europol statement on Thursday says it blocked bank accounts that laundered more than $370 000) for the organisation. It says 89 people were arrested and 39 victims rescued. The statement did not say when the operation took place. KEEP UPDATED on the latest news from around the continent by
